    {
      "step_id": "55dfc276",
      "step_index": 3,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "## 2) SAR REASONING (why these features matter for hERG)\n**Why it could block hERG**\n- **Cationic nitrogen**: hERG blockers commonly have a **protonated amine** that can engage in electrostatic interactions within the channel cavity (often discussed around acidic/polar residues and/or stabilization within the pore environment).\n- **Two aryl \u201chydrophobes\u201d**: aromatic rings can make **\u03c0 / hydrophobic contacts** with aromatic residues lining the hERG cavity (classically Tyr/Phe-rich regions), which is a major contributor to high affinity.\n- **Length/flexibility**: the **two 2-carbon linkers** plus an ether give conformational freedom and an overall span consistent with many known hERG blockers that can \u201creach\u201d key interaction regions in the pore.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T20:00:57.210726+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "65cb6064",
      "step_index": 4,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "**Why it might be weaker than a worst-case blocker**\n- **Two sulfonamides** substantially increase polarity and hydrogen-bonding/PSA, which can:\n  - reduce effective membrane partitioning into the channel environment,\n  - reduce \u201cgreasy\u201d hydrophobic binding energy compared with unsubstituted phenyls.\n- The rings are **not highly lipophilic** due to sulfonamide substitution; this can attenuate binding versus classic very lipophilic hERG binders.",
      "tool_name": null,
