      "content": "## 3) MECHANISTIC BASIS (how it would interact with hERG)\n- hERG blockers typically bind in the **inner cavity** accessible from the cytosolic side when the channel is open/inactivated.\n- This molecule likely adopts conformations where:\n  - the **protonated amine** sits centrally (electrostatic anchoring / desolvation-stabilized placement),\n  - the **two phenyl rings** occupy hydrophobic pockets and form **\u03c0-stacking / hydrophobic contacts** with cavity aromatics.\n- The **ether** can act as a conformational \u201chinge,\u201d helping the molecule fit different poses; flexibility generally increases the chance of finding a high-affinity binding conformation.",
